Nc3 b6 {This is the Queen's Indian Defense approach. Black fianchettoes his
queen's bishop before determining the position of his DSB. Typically, White
replies with} 5. cxd5 {to close the long diagonal for the black LSB.} exd5 ({
Black can keep the diagonal open with} 5... Nxd5 {but this comes at a cost of
giving up the central control to White:} 6. d4 Bb7 7. Bb5+ $1 {An important
intermezzo that forces} c6 {[%csl Rb7]} 8. Bd3 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Ge3e4]} Nxc3 9.
bxc3 Be7 10. O-O Nd7 11. e4 O-O 12. Bf4 {[%csl Yf4][%cal Rd8c7]} c5 13. Qe2 Nf6
14. h3 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] White has a pleasant version of the middlegame that
commonly appears in the Petrosian Variation of the QID. 1-0 (42) Lerner,K (2575
) -Quenette,R (2175) Metz 1998}) 6. g3 $5 {[%csl Rb7,Rd5,Yg3][%cal Gf1g2,
Gc8b7,Gf8d6,Rd6h2] This move is one of the cornerstones of the Keymer system,
and White has scored very well with it in practice. Even though we opened the
f1-a6 diagonal for our bishop -  as early as move two -  we change the plan and
intend to fianchetto it. This way of development has two advantages. Firstly,
from g2, the bishop can attack the d5-pawn more easily. Secondly, the g3-pawn
limits the impact of the black DSB, which is bound to be developed to d6.} Bb7
{This straightforward continuation is the most popular, although not
necessarily the most accurate one for Black.} ({It is more testing for White
if Black postpones the development of his LSB. This gives him the option to go
for ...Ba6 or ...Nbd7-c5 and exploit the weakness of d3-square in some
variations.} 6... Bd6 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Yc8a6,Yb8d7,Yd7c5,Gf1g2]} 7. Bg2 O-O ({
In the case of} 7... Ba6 {it is very important to rememeber that we have} 8. b4
$1 {[%cal Gb4b5,Rd6b4,Yd1a4]} O-O 9. b5 Bb7 10. O-O a6 11. Bb2 axb5 12. Nxb5
Be7 13. a4 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Yb2g7,Yg2b7] White has more active pieces and a
flexible central structure.} Nbd7 (13... c5 14. Qb1 $5 Nc6 15. d4 c4 16. Ne5
$14 {[%csl Gb5,Ge5][%cal Gb2c3,Yf2f4]}) 14. Qc2 c6 15. Nbd4 $1 $14 {[%csl Yd4]
[%cal Gd4f5] 1-0 (55) Keymer, V (2588) -Barp, A (2374) Chess.com INT 2020}) 8.
O-O Re8 9. Re1 $1 {A useful prophylaxis. It should be noted that White doesn't
rush pushing d2-d4 unless Black plays ...c5 himself first.} (9. b3 {allows
