of the f-pawn looks dangerous for Black.}) 12. O-O O-O 13. d4 {transposing
into the 9...Bd6 line.}) (9... Rc8 10. g3 $5 c5 11. Bg2 b5 {1-0 (41) Malakhov,V
(2666) -Banusz,T (2641) Struga 2021} 12. Ne5 $5 $146 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 $14 {
[%csl Rd5][%cal Ge2f4,Ge2c3]}) (9... g6 10. g3 $1 c5 11. Bg2 b5 {Black tries
to discourage d2-d4. However, White exploits his lag in development with:} 12.
O-O Bd6 13. d4 c4 14. Ne5 $1 $14 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gb3c4, Ye5c4] 1/2-1/2 (74)
Ganguly, S (2609) -Gukesh, D (2614) chess24.com INT 2022}) 10. Ned4 $1 {
[%cal Gd4f5] This is better} ({than} 10. g3 c5 11. Bg2 b5 $1 $13 {[%cal
Gd2d4,Gc5c4] which makes it difficult for White to push d2-d4 in favorable
circumstances due to the ...c5-c4 reply.}) 10... c5 11. Nf5 Bf8 12. Be2 {
White won't go for the double fianchetto, but he still gets reasonable chances
in the middledgame after} g6 13. Ng3 $1 {A precise move, keeping Black's
...h5-h4 plan in mind.} Bg7 14. O-O O-O 15. d4 $13 {Black has a good version
of the IQP, but White has his trumps, too. The following game is a good
example: transposing into the 9...Bd6 line.} Ne4 (15... h5 $5) (15... Rc8 $5)
16. Rc2 $1 {[%cal Gd1a1,Gf1c1]} Rc8 17. Qa1 Qe7 18. Rfc1 f5 19. a4 $1 {[%csl
Rc5][%cal Ga4a5]} a5 20. Bb5 $14 {[%csl Yb5,Rc5] 1-0 (40) Fataliyeva,U (2428)
-Beydullayeva,G (2387) Baku 2022} *

