{[%evp 0,33,20,20,22,9,9,6,10,10,16,15,8,8,4,-24,40,9,-8,-10,-11,-22,-5,-15,1,
7,7,-1,20,17,32,-1,22,30,20,10]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 c5 {
In this lecture, we will focus on variations where Black wants to equalize by
clearing up the center with ....c5 and/or ...dxc4 at the earliest opportunity.
These approaches are the equivalent of the Tarrasch defense and Queen's Gambit
Accepted. Indeed, we will see that the lines sometimes transpose from the
Keymer variation into one of these openings.} (4... a6 5. b3 c5 6. cxd5 exd5 7.
d4 {transposes to 4...c5 5.cxd5 exd5 6.d4 a6.}) 5. cxd5 {We want to determine
the central structure before pushing d2-d4. This way we eliminate the ...dxc4
option that Black had on the previous move. Black has two major possibilities
now:} exd5 {corresponds to the Tarrasch approach.} 6. d4 {Black has several
playable continuations at this point.} Nc6 {is the main line, which often
arises from the Symmetrical English: Four Knights move order.} (6... a6 {
[%cal Rf1b5,Yc5c4,Yb7b5] avoids the Bb5 lines and also prepares to clamp down
on the queenside with ...c4 and . ..b5. Therefore, I suggest} 7. b3 {[%cal
Rc5c4] Black has two options now. Keep the central tension with transposes to
4...c5 5.cxd5 exd5 6.d4 a6.} Nc6 ({or release it with} 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 (
8... Bb4 {looks tempting because it seems like White has to put his bishop on
the awkward d2-square to unpin. However,} 9. Bb2 $1 $146 {is very much
possible. Black cannot exploit the pin.} Ne4 (9... Nc6 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bd3
$14 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ge1g1] leaves the DSB misplaced on b4 after White castles.
}) 10. Qc2 Qa5 11. Nde2 $1 {This is the key move. White will play a2-a3 next
to invite favorable simplifications.} Bf5 12. a3 $1 Bxc3+ (12... Nxc3 13. Qxf5
$1 Ne4+ 14. axb4 Qxb4+ 15. Bc3 Nxc3 16. Qe5+ $18) 13. Bxc3 Nxc3 14. Qxc3 Qxc3+
15. Nxc3 Be6 16. O-O-O $14 {[%csl Rd5,Re6] with a typical stable endgame
advantage for White.}) 9. Bb2 {-7...cxd4} Bd6 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O Re8 {A
similar position is analyzed in Lecture 1. The difference is that Black has
spent a tempo on ...a6. This works in White's favor in this position, although
the margin for an advantage is still fairly minimal if Black plays accurately.}
12. Rc1 Nxd4 (12... Bc7 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Bf3 $1 {[%csl Yg1][%cal Gg2g3,Yf3g2]}
Qd6 15. g3 Bh3 16. Bg2 $14 {[%csl Rc6,Yg1][%cal Gc3a4] is very similar to a
corresponding position analyzed in Lecture 1.}) 13. Qxd4 Be5 14. Qd2 d4 {
The most direct attempt to equalize. Otherwise, White keeps at least a slight
edge.} (14... Bf5 15. Rfd1 {[%cal Rd5d4]} Qd6 16. f4 Bxc3 17. Qxc3 $14 {
[%csl Yb2,Yc3,Re3] /=}) (14... Ne4 15. Nxe4 Bxb2 16. Rcd1 $1 $16 {1-0 (42)
Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2643) -Berry,N (2247) La Massana 2013}) 15. exd4 Qxd4 16.
Qxd4 Bxd4 17. Bf3 $14 {[%csl Ra8,Rb7,Rc8][%cal Gf1d1] /=. The extra tempo
matters. Black still has some issues to solve.}) 8. Bb2 Bg4 (8... cxd4 9. Nxd4
{-7...cxd4}) {White has to release the tension due to the increased pressure on
d4.} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O {An important Tarrasch tabiya. White's
plan is to swap some pieces (usually starting with h3 Bh5, Nh4) and keep the
d4-square under control. Of course, Black's piece activity allows him to meet
this plan in several reasonable ways.} Re8 (11... Ba7 {is quite popular,
although slower compared to the alternatives.} 12. h3 Bh5 (12... Bf5 {avoids
the simplification via Nh4. In this case, White tries to exchange the bishops
with} 13. Bd3 {[%csl Yb2,Rd5][%cal Gc3e2,Ge2f4]} Be4 14. Nxe4 $1 {This works
tactically.} Nxe4 (14... dxe4 $6 {runs into} 15. Bxf6 $1 Qxd3 16. Qxd3 exd3 17.
Bc3 $16 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gf1d1,Gf3e1,Yd1d2,Ya1d1] and the d3-pawn looks like
an easy prey for the white pieces in the endgame.}) 15. Rc1 $14 {[%csl
Gb2,Gd3,Yd4] 1-0 (72) Alekseev,E (2591) -Khegay,D (2523) Sochi 2022}) 13. Nh4
Bg6 (13... Bxe2 14. Nxe2 $14) 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. Bf3 {[%csl Rd5]} d4 {[%cal
Yf3a8] Black has to play like this to avoid long-term problems with this pawn,
but he opens the diagonal for the white LSB.} 16. exd4 Bxd4 17. Bxc6 $1 bxc6
18. Na4 $14 {[%csl Ra6,Rc6] 0-1 (33) Lenderman,A (2570) -Predke,A (2684)
Chess.com INT 2022}) (11... Qd6 $5 {[%cal Ga8d8] might be a tad more accurate
than 11...Ba7.} 12. h3 Bh5 13. Nh4 Bg6 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. Bf3 Rad8 {[%csl Gd5]}
16. Ne2 $14 {[%csl Yb2,Rd5,Yf3] /=. White has a typical minimal edge thanks to
his bishop pair and some pressure against the d5-pawn. ½-½ (112) Yu, Y (2710)
-Robson, R (2684) Saint Louis 2022}) 12. h3 Bf5 $1 {This is the only move that
can challenge White's simplification plan.} (12... Bh5 $6 {runs into a
different problem:} 13. Na4 $1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb2f6]} Ba7 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15.
Qxd5 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Gd5h5] Here, we see why it was important to include 12.
h3. White wins the crucial tempo by attacking the black LSB on h5.}) 13. Bd3 {
Black can now put either piece on e4, and it's not convenient for White to
trade it.} Be4 (13... Ne4 {[%cal Rd3e4,Rc3e4] also leads to a complex position.
