Gb7b5,Yf8b4] is a rare but interesting attempt to clamp down on the queenside.
White can undermine this pawn with the following accurate continuation:} 7. Bd2
$1 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gb2b3]} a6 8. a4 $1 {[%cal Rb7b5]} Bb4 (8... Nc6 9. b3 cxb3
10. Qxb3 $14 {[%csl Rd5] /= gives White a favorable pawn structure in the long
run.}) 9. b3 Be6 $1 {The only way to justify Black's sixth move. However, it
looks risky to give White the big center, so many people wouldn't play it.} (
9... cxb3 10. Qxb3 Nc6 11. Bd3 $14) 10. bxc4 dxc4 11. Be2 Nc6 12. O-O O-O 13.
Qb1 $1 $14 {[%cal Gf1c1,Yf3g5,Ya1a2,Ya2b2,Yb1b7,Ye3e4] /=. A very nice move
that gives White a slight edge due to pressure on the b-file and the potential
for central expansion.}) 7. Bb5 {This pin is somewhat annoying for Black
because he cannot develop his pieces as freely as he would like.} cxd4 {
Interestingly, this is only the third most popular move in the position, but
it's considered the main line for Black on the top level. The idea is to
develop the DSB to d6 without losing a tempo.} ({This is precisely what
happens in the case of} 7... Bd6 {when White plays} 8. dxc5 Bxc5 {and Black
will need to spend an extra move to get his bishop back to the attacking h2-b8
diagonal.} 9. O-O O-O 10. b3 Bg4 (10... a6 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Bb2 {transposes
to the 7...a6 line.}) 11. Bb2 Rc8 12. h3 Bh5 13. Rc1 Bd6 {This extra tempo for
White does matter, as the following continuation shows:} 14. Be2 Bb8 15. Nh4 $1
({Alternatively,} 15. Nb5 $5 Ne4 16. Nfd4 $5 $146 {is a safe way to force a
trade of a couple of pieces and keep a slight edge.} Bxe2 17. Qxe2 $14 {
/=}) 15... Qd6 {The most popular move,} ({but Black should maybe consider the
less committal} 15... Bg6 $5 {when I'm not sure if White has anything better
than} 16. Nxg6 hxg6 17. Bf3 d4 18. exd4 Nxd4 19. g3 $1 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Yf3g2]}
Nxf3+ 20. Qxf3 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Rb8][%cal Gf1d1,Gc3e4] / =, keeping a slight
initiative that Black could probably eventually neutralize with precise play.})
16. g3 Bxe2 17. Nxe2 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gh4f5] Black's position is more
problematic than it might seem at first. He has to be careful not to lose
material on the very next move.} Ne5 {is his best reply,} (17... Ne4 $4 {
is a typical blitz blunder:} 18. Bxg7 $1 $18 {[%cal Gh4f5] 1-0 (32) Wei, Y (
2736) -Praggnanandhaa, R (2536) Chess.com INT 2019}) (17... Qe6 $6 {was played
