Re8 15. Qa5 $1 $14 {[%csl Ya5] is exactly what White wanted, keeping castling
options open and dominating the queenside.} Nf8 16. O-O Qg6 17. Rfc1 {[%csl
Rc6][%cal Ga5c7]} Bh3 18. Bf1 Bd7 19. Qc7 $1 {[%cal Gc7g3] The key maneuver,
which neutralizes Black's kingside attack.} Rec8 20. Qg3 Qxg3 21. hxg3 $14 {
[%csl Ra7,Yb2,Rc6,Yf1] 1-0 (53) Oliva Castaneda,K (2498) -Ladron de Guevara
Pinto,P (2346) Montcada 2017}) (14... Qg6 15. O-O h5 {1/2-1/2 (26) Richter,N (
2267) -Hagner, B (2034) Baden Baden 2021 shouldn't be a big deal since White
can simply play} 16. Kh1 $14 {and if Black goes all in with} h4 17. h3 f5 18.
Qa5 f4 19. exf4 Rxf4 20. Bc1 $1 $16 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gc1e3,Ya5d8] White
dominates on the dark squares.}) 15. a4 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gb2c3,Gb2a3]} Re8 {
0-1 (35) Sismeiro, M (2203) -Santos, J (2342) Gaia 2021 Black won two games in
this position so far, but I believe we have an important improvement in} 16.
Bc3 $5 $146 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gb3b4]} Qc7 17. b4 axb4 18. Bxb4 {[%csl Ga4][%cal
Ga4a7]} Re6 19. a5 Rg6 20. g3 $14 {[%cal Ge1g1]}) (9... Re8 $5 {might be the
best option for Black, but it takes a super-prepared opponent to play this
sophisticated move.} 10. Nxd6 Qxd6 11. d4 e4 12. Ne5 Nfd7 {This is a slightly
different version of the idea explored in the 9...Nc6 line. Black tempts his
opponent into castling, so that he can get a favorable version of the kingside
attack. However, we can still show some finesse in turn with} 13. Qd2 $5 $146 {
White postpones castling and anticipates ...Nc6, when the queen proves useful
on the dark squares.} (13. O-O Nc6 14. Nxc6 bxc6 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Ge8e6,Ge6h6]
gives Black easier targets on the kingside, while White is also not up to
speed with his queenside play. For example,} 15. a4 Re6 16. Ba3 Qc7 17. Qc2 Rh6
$40 {[%cal Yd7f6,Yd7f8] 1-0 (44) Keymer, V (2690) -Kobo, O (2548) Chess.com INT
2023}) 13... a5 $1 {This is the only equalizer, but Black would need to show
an extremely deep understanding of the position to play it.} (13... Nc6 14.
Nxc6 bxc6 15. Qa5 $1 $14 {[%cal Ye1c1,Yb2a3,Ye1g1,Ye1d2] is exactly what White
wanted, keeping castling options open and dominating the queenside.}) (13...
Nf8 {[%cal Gf7f6] , an attempt to trap the knight on e5, is strongly met by}
14. O-O f6 15. f4 $1 {[%cal Ye5g4,Yg4f2] White clears the f2-square for the
knight's retreat (via g4) . Meanwhile, any capture opens the position
favorably for the better-developed white pieces.} exf3 (15... fxe5 16. dxe5 Qd8
17. f5 Nc6 {White can play 18.e6 now, white a slight edge, but the most
dangerous continuation is} 18. Rf4 $3 Nxe5 19. Raf1 $40 {[%csl Yb2,Rc8,Rf8,Rg8]
[%cal Gf5f6,Yd2d4] preparing to open up the black king with f5-f6, when the
b2-bishop becomes a monster. Black's extra piece is of little importance when
White attacks with full force like this.}) 16. Nxf3 Nc6 17. Bd3 $14 {[%csl
Yb2,Gd3][%cal Gf3h4,Ga2a4,Yb2a3,Ya1e1]}) 14. Bb5 f6 {Another precise move.} ({
White seems to have slightly better chances to make his bishops count in the
case of} 14... Nc6 15. Rc1 Ndxe5 16. dxe5 Qg6 17. O-O $14 {[%csl Yb2][%cal
Gf2f4,Gb5c6] /=} Bh3 $6 18. f4 exf3 19. Rxf3 $16 {[%csl Rf7,Rg6][%cal
Gc1f1,Gf3g3]}) 15. Nxd7 Bxd7 16. Be2 $1 {keeping the bishop pair. After} Nc6
17. O-O $14 {[%csl Yb2,Ye2][%cal Ga2a3,Gb2c3,Gb3b4] /=, White's plus is very
minimal, and Black should be able to neutralize it without much trouble.
However, we can still press a bit with our bishop pair with little to no risk.}
) 10. Nfd4 Be5 (10... Be7 {preserves the bishop from exchange. Nevertheless,
White keeps the edge thanks to his strong Nd4 and Bb2.} 11. Rc1 a6 12. Nc3 Bd7
{[%cal Gb8c6]} (12... Nbd7 {is the other way to develop the knight. White is
still better after} 13. d3 Ne5 14. dxe4 dxe4 15. Qc2 $14 {[%csl Re4]}) 13. Na4
$1 Bd6 14. O-O $5 $146 {This seems more accurate} ({than} 14. Nc5 Bc8 15. O-O
Ra7 $6 (15... Nbd7 $13 {[%csl Yc5]}) 16. f4 $1 $16 {[%csl Ra7][%cal
Ye4f3,Ye2f3] 1/2-1/ 2 (70) Priyanka,N (2242) -Soumya,S (2384) Caleta 2020})
14... Nc6 15. Nc5 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 $14 {[%cal Gb3b4,Gd1b3,Rd2d3]}) 11. Ne6 $1 {
White wins the bishop pair thanks to this nice tactic.} fxe6 {[%cal
Gf8f2,Ye6e5] More dynamic than the alternative.} (11... Bxe6 12. Bxe5 Nc6 13.
Bb2 {[%csl Yb2][%cal Gb5d4] gives White a slight but lasting edge since Black
is quite static.}) 12. Bxe5 Nc6 (12... a6 13. Nd4 Qe7 14. f4 $1 $14 {[%csl Ye5]
/=}) 13. Bb2 $1 e5 {The critical continuation.} (13... a6 14. Nd4 $14 {[%cal
Re6e5] is quite pleasant for White since Black cannot justify doubling his
pawns on the e-file anymore.} Qd6 15. Rc1 Bd7 16. O-O Nb4 17. a3 Nd3 18. Bxd3
exd3 19. Nf3 $16 {[%csl Rd3,Ye5] 0-1 (58) Hagner,B (2323) -Rendle, T (2385)
Dusseldorf 2023}) 14. Ba3 a6 $1 {Taking on f8 doesn't quite work, so Black
gets away with this move.} 15. Nd6 Qa5 16. Qc1 {At the first glance, this
position looks very good for White because he will eliminate the other black
bishop. However, as the following game shows, it's not that easy for White to
demonstrate the advantage in a practical game due to Black's strong central
presence.} Rd8 17. Qb2 Qc7 18. Nxc8 Raxc8 19. O-O Kh8 $14 {[%csl Ra3,
Yd5,Re2,Ye4,Ye5][%cal Gd5d4] ; Bokar,J (2537) -Mayer,R (2490) ICCF GMN/A/01
email 2019 1/2-1/2 /=. Nevertheless, the long-term potential of the bishop pair
remains.} *

