[Annotator "GM Davorin Kuljasevic"]
[PlyCount "33"]
[EventDate "2023.??.??"]
[SourceVersionDate "2009.11.16"]

{[%evp 0,33,21,21,21,13,42,23,19,-3,15,-7,-6,-12,11,-9,-7,-12,-9,-29,-26,-14,3,
-19,-10,-10,6,-4,-13,-13,3,1,3,9,9,1]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 c5 {[%cal Yb8c6,Yc8g4,
Rc2c4,Yd5d4] This is the 'Principled approach' against the Keymer system.
Black takes the available space in the center and prepares to develop his
queenside pieces in the most active manner. He does not aim to get any
particular type of well-known defense, such as those discussed in the first
three lectures. Instead, this move has independent value, as Black discourages
3.c4 by preparing 3...d4. However, as usual in this system, White can use his
first move advantage to put pressure on the black center.} 3. b3 {I recommend
this move instead of 3.d4, which transposes to a good version of the Colle
attack for Black. As usual in the Reti/Keymer, we postpone the d-pawn advance
and focus on development first. In essence, we now get a Queen's Indian
Defense with colors reversed and an extra tempo for White. Our goal is to make
that tempo count and build on our slight development advantage. Black has a
wide choice of replies to choose from. We can group them in the following way:
1) Layman's approach (...Nc6/...Nf6) 2) Reversed Petrosian QID (...a5/...Nc6) 3
) Reversed Fianchetto QID (...Nf6, g6) 4) Reversed e3-QID (...Nf6, e6) 5)
Ambitious ...f6 (with or without ...Nc6)} Nc6 ({The main alternative is} 3...
Nf6 4. Bb2 {and now Black has a couple of options. The best, in my view, is} g6
$5 {which is still relatively unpopular compared to the alternatives. Black
wants to play the Fianchetto variation of the QID with reversed colors.} (4...
e6 {a more popular move, leads to the reversed 4.e3 QID. As usual, when Black
decides to leave his LSB at home,' we play} 5. d4 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Rc8g4]} Nc6
{[%csl Rc8][%cal Gf1d3,Gb1d2,Yf3e5,Yf2f4] Now, we are firmly in the Colle
attack territory.} (5... cxd4 6. exd4 g6 {[%csl Yg7][%cal Gf8g7] is an attempt
to finesse this line, but it also has a downside} 7. Nbd2 Bg7 8. Ba3 $5 {
[%csl Rg7][%cal Ge8g8]} ({White could also play the usual} 8. Bd3 Nc6 9. O-O
O-O 10. Ne5 {[%csl Rd3,Gf7,Gg6,Gh7][%cal Gd2f3,Rd3g6] but then Black will
claim that he is better prepared for White's kingside attack, thanks to his
fianchetto.}) 8... Bf8 {This has to be played sooner or later. The trade of
DSB is slightly in White's favor considering the vulnerability of Black's
dark-square complex.} 9. Bxf8 Kxf8 10. Bd3 Kg7 11. O-O Nc6 12. a3 a6 13. Re1
$14 {[%csl Ye5,Yf6,Yg5,Rg7,Yh6] 1-0 (65) Firouzja,A (2749) -Nakamura, H (2736)
Chess.com INT 2020}) (5... Be7 {is a clever move order on the surface, but it
allows White to win a tempo with} 6. dxc5 $5 ({Black's idea is to postpone the
development of the queen's knight in order to enable the following maneuver:}
6. Bd3 {[%csl Yb8][%cal Yb8c6]} O-O 7. Nbd2 b6 8. O-O Ba6 $5 {[%csl Ra6,Yb8,
Gd3][%cal Yb8a6] The trade of the LSB's would reduce White's attacking
potential significantly.}) 6... Bxc5 7. c4 {We are now playing the QGA with
reversed colors and two extra tempi for White (b3 and Bb2) . The World's #1,
Magnus Carlsen, played several instructive games in similar positions,
